<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ901224-0101</DOCNO><DOCID>901224-0101.</DOCID><HL>   Horn andamp; Hardart Co.   Says It Plans to Exit   Restaurant Business</HL><DATE>12/24/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 10</SO><CO>   HOR</CO><IN>RESTAURANTS, FAST-FOOD, CATERING (RES)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   WEEHAWKEN, N.J. -- Horn andamp; Hardart Co., best-known forcreating the American automat cafeteria, is getting out ofthe restaurant business.   The company said it will sell its last restaurantbusiness, International King's Table, to focus on itsdirect-mail marketing business.</LP><TEXT>   Last Friday, the company said it will be taking asignificant fourth-quarter charge resulting from itsdivestiture of the restaurant business, which it plans tocomplete by the end of March. International King, whichoperates 83 buffet-style restaurants in the West coast, had a$5.2 million net loss in the first nine months of this year.   The divestiture marks Horn andamp; Hardart's exit from its oncecore restaurant business in favor of Hanover Direct Inc., itsdirect-marketing concern. In the past year, the company hassold or is trying to sell nearly all of its East Coastrestaurant holdings, including Bojangles' Fried Chicken 'NBiscuits, Tony Roma's Italian restaurants in New York andArby's in southern Florida.   According to Jack E. Rosenfeld, president and chiefexecutive of Horn andamp; Hardart, the company decision to changeits line of business was motivated by continuing losses inits diverse restaurant holdings. &quot;With 10 years of tryingmany facets of the restaurant business, the company wasn'table to make any kind of return on it,&quot; he said.   For the third-quarter, Horn andamp; Hardart reported a net lossof $3.2 million, or 23 cents a share, compared with a netloss of $1.6 million, or 12 cents a share, the previous year.   Hanover Direct is expected to report a 44% increase inrevenue this year to $550 million from $382 million in 1989.</TEXT></DOC>